context.conversationSummary:
USER: give me roadmap for springboot
AI: 😊 Hey there, Darshan! I'm excited to guide you through setting up a **Spring Boot** application. Here’s your step-by-step "roadmap" tailored just for Spring Boot:

1. Install Java Development Kit (JDK) if not already installed since it is required by most IDEs and build tools like Maven or Gradle which we'll be using soon. For a quick setup, you can download JDK from the Oracle website [here](https://www.oracle.com/java/).

2. Install an Integrated Development Environment (IDE) such as **IntelliJ IDEA** with Spring plugins enabled for convenience and enhanced productivity if not already installed: https://www.jetbrains.com/idea/. If you're using Eclipse, check out the [Spring Tool Suite](https://spring.io/tools).

3. Set up a project structure in your IDE by creating a new Spring Boot Project with appropriate dependencies like `spring-boot-starter`, which will manage all necessary configurations for us:
   - **IntelliJ** and other supported plugins can handle this automatically, just select the 'Spring Initializer' or create from template.

4. Write your first simple Java class to demonstrate how easy it is with Spring Boot:
```java
package com.example;

import org.springframework.boot.CommandLineRunner;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import java.util.stream.Stream;

@Configuration
class DemoConfig implements CommandLineRunner {
    @Override
    public void run(String... args) throws Exception {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

5. Add the main class to your `src` folder and configure it as follows:
   ```java
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApp.class, args);
    }
}
   ```
6. Run your application by right-clicking on the project in IntelliJ or using Maven/Gradle's `mvn spring-boot:run`/`gradle bootRun`. You should see "Hello, World!" printed to console indicating successful setup and running of a Spring Boot Application! 🎉

That’s it for now. As you get more comfortable with the basics, I can guide you through creating REST APIs, integrating databases, or even setting up microservices if that's where your interest lies next. Keep coding, Darshan! If you need anything else just let me know. 😊

--- Take your time.

